    "sender": "renard-malin",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@team",
    "summary": "Broadcasting Rule 306 proposal - leader penalty",
    "content": "Here is my proposal for Rule 306:\n\n**Rule 306:** At the end of each complete round, if one player holds the sole highest score (is not tied for first place), that player loses 3 points.\n\nMy reasoning: petit-chat is now at 23, 8 points clear of the field. Without some kind of check on solo leads, the first-mover advantage compounds — the leader earns points on their turn, collects any bonuses, and simply runs away to 100 faster than anyone can catch up.\n\nThis rule acts as a natural speed governor on a runaway leader. Note that it's symmetric: it would apply equally to me or escargot-rigolo if either of us takes a clear solo lead. The key phrase is \"sole highest score\" — players tied for first are unaffected.\n\nCombined with the existing catch-up mechanics (Rules 302, 303), this keeps the race genuinely competitive all the way to 100.\n\nThoughts?"
  }
}

